<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,294,319]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This genus can be separated from the other Australian 
<taxonomicName box="[940,1097,294,319]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Stratiomyidae</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: Eyes distinctly separated in both sexes and with sparse ommatrichia. Flagellomeres indistinct, at most represented by slight dorsal and/or ventral indentations; the first flagellomere is sometimes present in 
<taxonomicName authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M. robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[274,364,402,427]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp.</emphasis>
Wings of male lacking discal medial cell, vein M 
<number box="[928,936,417,431]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="3.0">3</number>
absent; females apterous. Scutum of female without dorsal sutures and scutellum absent; scutum of male with usual sutures and scutellum present. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[280,381,477,502]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[338,381,477,502]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
</figureCitation>
) small; aedeagus single pronged. Gonocoxite medially attenuate distally, extending almost to apex of aedeagus. Epandrium (
<figureCitation box="[516,594,513,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Figs 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[611,640,513,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">26</figureCitation>
) with prominent posterior corners. Female terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[1288,1423,513,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[187,1351,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[187,1351,193,1905]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 15. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., female paratypes. (9). Head, lateral view. (10). Head, frontal view. (11). Lateral habitus. (12). Dorsal habitus. (13). Terminalia, dorsal view. (14). Terminalia, lateral view. (15). Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: ce, cercus; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266436/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[1350,1423,513,538]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor not apparent; sternite 
<number box="[520,534,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
viewed ventrally, is convex and longer than combined length of tergites 
<number box="[1347,1361,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<number box="[1415,1432,550,574]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.0">9</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,413,585,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Description. Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[427,529,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[485,496,586,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="1.0">1</number>
–8
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[541,616,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
22– 
<number box="[587,616,585,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[635,698,585,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[714,815,585,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[771,781,586,610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="1.0">1</number>
–2
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[828,859,586,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">23</figureCitation>
). Yellow-brown with short erect setae; transversely broadened; ocellar tubercle black or black brown and raised above vertex. Frons visible when viewed laterally especially in 
<taxonomicName authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[303,458,657,681]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis box="[303,458,657,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M. robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[467,551,657,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp</emphasis>
. Frontal index 
<number box="[730,817,657,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="0.65" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.8</number>
. Ratio of frons width to head width 1.0:2.0– 
<number box="[1331,1369,657,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="2.6">2.6</number>
. Eyes distinctly separated and with sparse ommatrichia. Flagellomeres indistinct, at most represented by slight dorsal and/or ventral indentations; the first flagellomere is sometimes present in 
<taxonomicName authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[977,1130,729,753]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis box="[977,1130,729,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M. robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1136,1218,729,754]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,288,765,790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Thorax</emphasis>
about 
<number box="[375,410,765,790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times longer than wide and entirely yellowish brown or deep brown, with scutellum, humeral callus, postalar callus and laterotergite yellowish. Anepisternum shining, mostly devoid of setae. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[159,230,837,862]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[216,230,838,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[287,316,838,862]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<number box="[287,316,838,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
) about 
<number box="[402,436,837,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="2.5">2.5</number>
–3.0 times longer than wide and lacking discal medial cell and vein M 
<number box="[1235,1243,852,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="3.0">3</number>
. Legs yellowish. First tarsomere on all legs shorter or longer than tibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,912,937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Abdomen</emphasis>
yellowish uniformly covered with short suberect setae. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[1148,1250,912,937]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1927]" captionTargetBox="[171,1383,193,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[171,1383,193,1869]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., male paratypes. (1). Head, lateral view. (2). Head, anterior view. (3). Lateral habitus. (4). Wing. (5). Antenna. (6). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (7). Genital capsule, ventral view. (8). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; gonocx, gonocoxite; gonost, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266435/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[1206,1221,912,937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="6.0">6</number>
–8
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1263,1335,912,937]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 26" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1762,1785]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,551,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,551,1740]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 26. Metridius mcalpinei nov. sp., male paratypes. (22). Lateral habitus. (23). Head, lateral view. (24). Wing. (25). Genital capsule, dorsal view with epandrium, proctiger and cerci excluded. (26). Epandrium, proctiger and cerci. Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; ce, cercus; ep, epandrium; goncx, gonocoxite; gonst, gonostylus; pr, poctiger. Scale bar, 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
25– 
<number box="[1306,1335,912,937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
) broadly triangular to subquadrate. Cerci one segmented. Gonostyli concave distally. Aedeagus single pronged. Gonocoxite medially attenuate distally, extending almost to apex of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1020,1045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[303,422,1020,1045]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[187,1351,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[187,1351,193,1905]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 15. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., female paratypes. (9). Head, lateral view. (10). Head, frontal view. (11). Lateral habitus. (12). Dorsal habitus. (13). Terminalia, dorsal view. (14). Terminalia, lateral view. (15). Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: ce, cercus; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266436/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[363,422,1020,1045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="12.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="9.0">9–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Differing from male by being apterous and lacking halters, scutellum and most lateral thoracic pleura. Head (figs 
<number box="[456,517,1056,1080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="9.0">9–10</number>
). Frontal index 
<number box="[693,781,1056,1081]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="0.6499999999999999" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.7</number>
. Ratio of frons width to head width 1.0: 
<number box="[1234,1322,1056,1081]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="2.55" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.5">2.5–2.6</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,294,1092,1117]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Thorax.</emphasis>
Scutum without dorsal sutures and scutellum. Wings absent, halters absent. Legs shorter than male and first tarsomere shorter than tibiae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1164,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[473,607,1164,1189]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[187,1351,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[187,1351,193,1905]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 15. Metridius robertsoni nov. sp., female paratypes. (9). Head, lateral view. (10). Head, frontal view. (11). Lateral habitus. (12). Dorsal habitus. (13). Terminalia, dorsal view. (14). Terminalia, lateral view. (15). Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: ce, cercus; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266436/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
Figs 
<number box="[533,607,1164,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor is not apparent; sternite 
<number box="[1046,1060,1165,1189]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
viewed ventrally is convex and longer than combined length of tergites 
<number box="[598,612,1200,1224]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<number box="[667,684,1200,1224]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.0">9</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1236,1261]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the genus comes from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[913,1019,1236,1260]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">metridios</emphasis>
, filled with seed, pertaining to the enlarged ovaries of the 
<typeStatus box="[413,461,1273,1297]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">type</typeStatus>
species which occupy most of the abdominal and thoracic cavities.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" box="[199,1029,1308,1333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1308,1333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Geographic Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[506,609,1308,1333]" name="Australia" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Australia</collectingCountry>
(Queensland and New South 
<collectingCountry box="[944,1017,1308,1333]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Wales</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="574" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1344,1369]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Comments.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[345,454,1344,1368]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[464,573,1344,1369]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[730,806,1345,1368]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[730,806,1345,1368]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having eyes with sparse ommatrichia; in males the flagellum is at least three times as long as the combined length of the scape and pedicel, and the eyes are distinctly separated; females are apterous and lack scutal sutures and scutellum. From 
<taxonomicName box="[1021,1133,1416,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1021,1133,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName box="[1233,1355,1416,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1233,1355,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, 
<emphasis box="[151,260,1452,1476]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[268,374,1452,1477]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
differs in having an almost flat frons. Female 
<taxonomicName box="[904,1017,1452,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[904,1017,1452,1476]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are micropterous, having vestiges of the wings and halters, in 
<taxonomicName authority="Macquart, 1847" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1847" box="[443,599,1488,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Metoponia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robertsoni">
<emphasis box="[443,466,1489,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[483,599,1488,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">robertsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[608,699,1488,1513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. sp.</emphasis>
they are entirely absent. The ovipositor of 
<taxonomicName box="[1202,1314,1488,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1202,1314,1488,1512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and many 
<taxonomicName box="[151,273,1524,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,273,1524,1548]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is comprised of segments 
<number box="[586,631,1524,1549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="6.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="5.0">5–8</number>
; in 
<taxonomicName box="[678,754,1525,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[678,754,1525,1548]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the ovipositor is comprised of segments 
<number box="[1236,1250,1525,1548]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="7.0">7</number>
and 
<number box="[1311,1326,1525,1549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
, while in 
<emphasis box="[151,260,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[267,371,1560,1585]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
the ovipositor is not well developed. Sternite 
<quantity box="[887,930,1560,1585]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[936,1058,1560,1584]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[936,1058,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1072,1148,1561,1584]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1072,1148,1561,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1203,1316,1560,1584]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1316,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more or less flat and tapers distally, in 
<taxonomicName box="[496,572,1597,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[496,572,1597,1620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is almost square, in 
<taxonomicName box="[833,946,1596,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[833,946,1596,1620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1003,1125,1596,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1125,1596,1620]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is about twice as long as wide; in 
<emphasis box="[248,357,1632,1656]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[364,469,1632,1657]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
sternite 
<number box="[564,578,1632,1656]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
is convex, its length subequal to its basal width, and the apical margin about half the basal width. Tergite 
<number box="[495,509,1669,1693]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and sternite 
<number box="[668,682,1669,1693]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
are subequal in length in 
<taxonomicName box="[1001,1113,1668,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Boreoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1001,1113,1668,1692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Boreoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1132,1208,1669,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Inopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1132,1208,1669,1692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Inopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1272,1394,1668,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Chiromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1272,1394,1668,1692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Chiromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; in 
<emphasis box="[151,260,1704,1728]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">Metridius</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[267,371,1704,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574">nov. gen.</emphasis>
, the combined length of tergites 
<number box="[741,755,1704,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<number box="[809,823,1704,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="9.0">9</number>
approximates the length of sternite 
<number box="[1226,1242,1704,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" value="8.0">8</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
